{{translated page|ja|天宮神社の十二段舞楽|version=93621864|comment=Imported full ja history}}

'''Tengū Shrine’s Twelve-Step Bugaku''' (天宮神社の十二段舞楽, Amemiya Jinja no Jūnidangaku) is a traditional folk performing art of {{ill|Bugaku|ja|舞楽|qq=draft|qq=draft}} passed down in {{ill|Morimachi, Shizuoka|ja|森町|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Shizuoka Prefecture|ja|静岡県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, specifically in the Tengū area of {{ill|Shūchi District, Shizuoka|ja|周智郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. It is one of the regionalized forms of Bugaku handed down in the {{ill|Tōkai region|ja|東海地方|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, performed annually on the first Saturday and Sunday of April.

The performance takes place on the stage of the {{ill|Bugaku Hall|ja|舞楽殿|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, featuring railings in front of the {{ill|Haiden|ja|拝殿|qq=draft|qq=draft}} of the {{ill|Tengū Shrine|ja|天宮神社|1=Ame-no-Miya Shrine|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. The dancers include four children, boys around 15 years old, and 11 adults. Accompaniment is provided by large drums, gongs, small drums, and flutes. The repertoire consists of 12 pieces: "Enbu" (延舞), "Iroka" (色香), "Niwa Chō" (庭胡蝶), "Tori-na" (鳥名), "Taihei-raku" (太平楽), "Shin Makka" (新靺鞨), "Ama" (安摩), "Ni no Mai" (二の舞), "Ryōō" (陵王), "Bato" (抜頭), "Nasu" (納曽利), and "Shishi" (獅子).

On {{ill|December 25, 1976|ja|1976年12月25日|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, it was selected as an {{ill|Intangible Folk Cultural Property in need of measures such as recording|ja|記録作成等の措置を講ずべき無形の民俗文化財|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Later, on {{ill|January 14, 1982|ja|1982nd year 1月14日|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, it was designated as an {{ill|Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property|ja|重要無形民俗文化財|qq=draft|qq=draft}} alongside the {{ill|Yamana Shrine Tenno Festival Bugaku|ja|山名神社天王祭舞楽|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and the {{ill|Oguni Shrine’s Bugaku|ja|小国神社の舞楽|qq=draft|qq=draft}} under the collective name "Bugaku of Morimachi in Tōtōmi" (遠江森町の舞楽).

