'''Tengū Shrine’s Twelve-Step Bugaku''' (天宮神社の十二段舞楽, Amemiya Jinja no Jūnidangaku) is a traditional folk performing art of {{ill|Bugaku|ja|舞楽|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bugaku|qq=}} passed down in {{ill|Morimachi, Shizuoka|ja|森町|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Morimachi, Shizuoka|qq=}}, [[:en:Shizuoka Prefecture|Shizuoka Prefecture]], specifically in the Tengū area of [[:en:Shūchi District, Shizuoka|Shūchi District, Shizuoka]]. It is one of the regionalized forms of Bugaku handed down in the [[:en:Tōkai region|Tōkai region]], performed annually on the first Saturday and Sunday of April.

The performance takes place on the stage of the {{ill|Bugaku Hall|ja|舞楽殿|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bugaku Hall|qq=}}, featuring railings in front of the [[:en:Haiden (Shinto)|Haiden]] of the {{ill|Tengū Shrine|ja|天宮神社|1=Ame-no-Miya Shrine|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tengū Shrine|13=User:Immanuelle/Ame-no-Miya Shrine|qq=}}. The dancers include four children, boys around 15 years old, and 11 adults. Accompaniment is provided by large drums, gongs, small drums, and flutes. The repertoire consists of 12 pieces: "Enbu" (延舞), "Iroka" (色香), "Niwa Chō" (庭胡蝶), "Tori-na" (鳥名), "Taihei-raku" (太平楽), "Shin Makka" (新靺鞨), "Ama" (安摩), "Ni no Mai" (二の舞), "Ryōō" (陵王), "Bato" (抜頭), "Nasu" (納曽利), and "Shishi" (獅子).

