The performance takes place on the stage of the {{ill|Bugaku Hall|ja|舞楽殿|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bugaku Hall|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, featuring railings in front of the [[:en:Haiden (Shinto)|Haiden]] of the {{ill|Tengū Shrine|ja|天宮神社|1=Ame-no-Miya Shrine|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tengū Shrine|13=User:Immanuelle/Ame-no-Miya Shrine|qq=}}. The dancers include four children, boys around 15 years old, and 11 adults. Accompaniment is provided by large drums, gongs, small drums, and flutes. The repertoire consists of 12 pieces: "Enbu" (延舞), "Iroka" (色香), "Niwa Chō" (庭胡蝶), "Tori-na" (鳥名), "Taihei-raku" (太平楽), "Shin Makka" (新靺鞨), "Ama" (安摩), "Ni no Mai" (二の舞), "Ryōō" (陵王), "Bato" (抜頭), "Nasu" (納曽利), and "Shishi" (獅子).

On {{ill|December 25, 1976|ja|1976年12月25日|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/December 25, 1976|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, it was selected as an {{ill|Intangible Folk Cultural Properties Requiring Documentation|lt=Intangible Folk Cultural Properties Requiring Documentation|lt=Intangible Folk Cultural Property in need of measures such as recording|ja|記録作成等の措置を講ずべき無形の民俗文化財|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Intangible Folk Cultural Property in need of measures such as recording|qq=}}. Later, on {{ill|January 14, 1982|ja|1982nd year 1月14日|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/January 14, 1982|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, it was designated as an {{ill|Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property|ja|重要無形民俗文化財|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property|qq=|1=Important Intangible Folk Cultural Properties of Japan|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q6573893}} alongside the {{ill|Yamana Shrine Tenno Festival Bugaku|ja|山名神社天王祭舞楽|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamana Shrine Tenno Festival Bugaku|qq=}} and the {{ill|Oguni Shrine’s Bugaku|ja|小国神社の舞楽|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Oguni Shrine’s Bugaku|qq=|1=Oguni Shrine’s Bugaku|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11459369}} under the collective name "Bugaku of Morimachi in Tōtōmi" (遠江森町の舞楽).

